INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '601d56a9-2e2d-42a4-a672-9d55288d3ac5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular State Management — Local, Lifted, Service, and Store: When to Use Each$escape$,
  $escape$Angular gives you four tiers of state management, and picking the wrong tier is the most common architecture mistake.

**Local state** (`signal()` inside a component) handles ephemeral UI — dropdown open, tab index, form dirty flag. Never reach outside the component for this.

**Lifted state** passes a signal or plain value via `@Input()` with change notification via `output()` (Angular 17+) or `EventEmitter`. Use this when two siblings share state through a common parent — no service needed yet.

**Service state** is an injectable with `providedIn: 'root'` (or scoped to a route) holding `signal()` or `BehaviorSubject`. Right for cross-component state that doesn't need time-travel or DevTools — user preferences, auth status, a paginated list.

**External store** (`@ngrx/signals` SignalStore or classic NgRx) adds action logs, selectors, and effects. Justify the boilerplate only when you need reproducible state, complex async flows, or team-scale predictability.

The signal APIs in Angular 16+ blur the lines — a well-typed injectable with `signal()` + `computed()` covers most "store" needs without NgRx overhead.$escape$,
  $escape$// auth.state.ts — service-level signal state (no NgRx needed)
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class AuthState {
  private _user = signal<User | null>(null);

  readonly user = this._user.asReadonly();
  readonly isLoggedIn = computed(() => this._user() !== null);

  login(user: User) { this._user.set(user); }
  logout()          { this._user.set(null); }
}

// In any component
export class NavComponent {
  auth = inject(AuthState);
  // template: {{ auth.isLoggedIn() ? 'Logout' : 'Login' }}
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
