INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '59aeb1f6-02ee-49e3-bb5b-3f2f7b91ac9d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Angular WebSockets — Singleton Connection, Reconnection, and Optimistic UI$escape$,
  $escape$Angular's dependency injection makes WebSocket management clean: provide a single service at the root level so every component shares one connection. Use RxJS `webSocket()` from `rxjs/webSocket` — it returns a `WebSocketSubject` that handles serialization automatically. For reconnection, pipe through `retryWhen` (or `retry({ delay: ... })` in RxJS 7+) combined with `timer` to implement exponential backoff without manual interval management.

For optimistic UI on message send: update your local `BehaviorSubject` state immediately before calling `socket$.next(payload)`. If the server ACKs with a correlation ID, reconcile — otherwise roll back on error using `catchError`. This keeps the UI snappy without waiting on round-trip latency.

Avoid creating `new WebSocket()` directly inside components — that spawns duplicate connections on re-render or route change. The `providedIn: 'root'` singleton survives navigation and reconnects transparently. Expose the stream as an `Observable` from the service; components only subscribe, never hold the subject reference.$escape$,
  $escape$@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class WsService {
  private socket$ = webSocket<Message>('wss://api.example.com/ws');
  private messages$ = new BehaviorSubject<Message[]>([]);

  readonly stream$ = this.socket$.pipe(
    retry({ delay: (_, count) => timer(Math.min(1000 * 2 ** count, 30000)) })
  );

  send(payload: Message): void {
    // Optimistic update
    this.messages$.next([...this.messages$.value, payload]);
    this.socket$.next(payload);
  }

  getMessages(): Observable<Message[]> {
    return this.messages$.asObservable();
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
